         <div subtype="original" type="letter" xml:id="L.6278" xml:lang="en">
            <pb facs="#IMG.1" n="1"/>
            <pb facs="#IMG.2" n="2"/>
            <dateline>Queen’s Coll. Oxford. April 13/ 85.</dateline>
            <opener>Dear Sir, </opener>
            <p>You were right in supposing that I have again been passing the winter in <placeName ref="[authorityLink]">Egypt</placeName>. I am but just returned; hence my delay in answering your letter. – I shall be very glad to be the means of introducing the results of your linguistic researches to the readers of the <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.subjects#S.4157">
                  <hi rend="unknown" rendition="#none">Academy</hi>
               </ref> &amp; the English public, &amp; I am glad to find that you were satisfied with my account of your Kreol Studies<note n="1" place="foot" type="editorial">Siehe hierzu auch Brief <ref target="https://gams.uni-graz.at/o:hsa.letter.6277">1-09979</ref>
               </note>. I wish that the Editor had allowed me to write a longer &amp; fuller notice of them.</p>
            <closer>
               <salute>Yours truly</salute>
               <signed>
                  <persName ref="[authorityLink]">A. H. Sayce.</persName>
               </signed>
            </closer>
         </div>
